Time Model Statistics

  • DB Time represents total time in user calls
  • DB CPU represents CPU time of foreground processes
  • Total CPU Time represents foreground and background processes
  • Statistics including the word "background" measure background process time, therefore do not contribute to the DB time statistic
  • Ordered by % of DB time in descending order, followed by Statistic Name

Finding 2: Shared Pool Latches
Impact is 28.14 active sessions, 68.11% of total activity.
----------------------------------------------------------
Contention for latches related to the shared pool was consuming significant
database time.
Waits for "library cache: mutex X" amounted to 2% of database time.
Waits for "library cache lock" amounted to 21% of database time.
Waits for "cursor: mutex X" amounted to 20% of database time.
Waits for "cursor: mutex S" amounted to 1% of database time.
Waits for "cursor: pin S wait on X" amounted to 22% of database time.

   No recommendations are available.

   Symptoms That Led to the Finding:
   ---------------------------------
      Wait class "Concurrency" was consuming significant database time.
      Impact is 28.44 active sessions, 68.86% of total activity.


Finding 3: "User I/O" wait Class
Impact is 2.12 active sessions, 5.14% of total activity.
--------------------------------------------------------
Wait class "User I/O" was consuming significant database time.
The throughput of the I/O subsystem was not significantly lower than expected.

   No recommendations are available.


Finding 4: Commits and Rollbacks
Impact is 1.85 active sessions, 4.49% of total activity.
--------------------------------------------------------
Waits on event "log file sync" while performing COMMIT and ROLLBACK operations
were consuming significant database time.

   Recommendation 1: Application Analysis
   Estimated benefit is 1.85 active sessions, 4.49% of total activity.
   -------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Investigate application logic for possible reduction in the number of
      COMMIT operations by increasing the size of transactions.
   Rationale
      The application was performing 56835 transactions per minute with an
      average redo size of 5316 bytes per transaction.

   Recommendation 2: Host Configuration
   Estimated benefit is 1.85 active sessions, 4.49% of total activity.
   -------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Investigate the possibility of improving the performance of I/O to the
      online redo log files.
   Rationale
      The average size of writes to the online redo log files was 7 K and the
      average time per write was 0 milliseconds.
   Rationale
      The total I/O throughput on redo log files was 12 M per second for reads
      and 9.9 M per second for writes.
   Rationale
      The redo log I/O throughput was divided as follows: 0% by RMAN and
      recovery, 45% by Log Writer, 0% by Archiver, 0% by Streams AQ and 54% by
      all other activity.

   Symptoms That Led to the Finding:
   ---------------------------------
      Wait class "Commit" was consuming significant database time.
      Impact is 1.85 active sessions, 4.49% of total activity.


Finding 5: PL/SQL Execution
Impact is 1.49 active sessions, 3.6% of total activity.
-------------------------------------------------------
PL/SQL execution consumed significant database time.

   Recommendation 1: SQL Tuning
   Estimated benefit is 1.42 active sessions, 3.44% of total activity.
   -------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Tune the entry point PL/SQL "TDS.OBJECTLOCK.REQUEST_LOCK" of type
      "PACKAGE" and ID 532424. Refer to the PL/SQL documentation for addition
      information.
   Rationale
      Subprogam ID 15 of PL/SQL ID 6347 spent 1041 seconds in execution.

   Recommendation 2: SQL Tuning
   Estimated benefit is .07 active sessions, .16% of total activity.
   -----------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Tune the entry point PL/SQL "TDS.OBJECTLOCK.RELEASE_LOCK" of type
      "PACKAGE" and ID 532424. Refer to the PL/SQL documentation for addition
      information.


Finding 6: DBMS_LOCK Usage
Impact is 1.36 active sessions, 3.29% of total activity.
--------------------------------------------------------
Waits for locks obtained by using the "DBMS_LOCK" package were consuming
significant database time.

   Recommendation 1: Application Analysis
   Estimated benefit is 1.36 active sessions, 3.29% of total activity.
   -------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Investigate application logic that uses the "DBMS_LOCK" package.
      Consider reducing the time these locks are held by the application or
      consider using a finer granularity of locks.
   Rationale
      The SQL statement with SQL_ID "5p51vnz5qzkcs" was found waiting for a
      lock when using "DBMS_LOCK".
      Related Object
         SQL statement with SQL_ID 5p51vnz5qzkcs.
         call objectLock.request_lock(:1 ,:2 ,:3 ,:4 )

   Symptoms That Led to the Finding:
   ---------------------------------
      Wait class "Application" was consuming significant database time.
      Impact is 1.36 active sessions, 3.29% of total activity.
